00:06:32.200 --> 00:06:35.300
Okay, let's talk a little bit
about how this works.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:44.480
We have a Speech Recognition
engine which has a well-documented,

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:44.480
mature API,
and applications can call this engine.

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:48.990
We ship some applications that call it,
and some of you guys do,

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:51.630
and we hope after today more of you will.

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:54.080
The Speech Recognition
Engine itself has a number of

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:55.890
characteristics that are important.

00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:57.780
First of all, it's speaker independent.

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:00.520
You don't have to train it to your voice.

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:03.450
You just open it up and turn
it straight on and use it.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:06.300
For example,
I had trashed the preferences

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:09.670
just before we came up,
so what you've seen me do here

00:07:09.670 --> 00:07:11.800
is straight out of the OS X CD.

00:07:11.940 --> 00:07:15.070
There's no adaptation to your voice.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:25.460
Secondly,
it's a continuous speech engine.

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:25.460
You don't have to pause between words,
which is a great relief.

00:07:25.690 --> 00:07:29.040
It's a continuous speech engine
and it has a large vocabulary.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:32.060
We have 120,000 words in the dictionary.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:36.500
If a word is not in the dictionary,
then we decompose it linguistically.

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:39.610
We know about known endings and
word components and look up its

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:42.060
stems in the dictionary and then
reconstruct its pronunciation.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:45.100
If that doesn't work,
then we fall through to statistically

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:48.180
trained letter-to-sound rules,
trained with classification

00:07:48.180 --> 00:07:51.020
and regression trees,
and we have different sets of rules

00:07:51.020 --> 00:07:52.820
for names and for the rest of English.

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:55.470
So it's a large vocabulary engine.

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.100
And we use it for command and control.

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:01.640
The way we do this is driving
it by a finite state grammar.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:05.320
That means to call the engine,
you tell it what to listen for.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:07.940
You express that as,
in the simplest case,

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:11.870
a flat list of commands,
or you can give it a full grammar,

00:08:11.880 --> 00:08:17.610
such as set up a meeting
with name at time,

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:21.300
where within the grammar,
name would then expand to, say,

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:22.820
all of the names in your address book.

