you were working at your desk,

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:41.100
sometimes there will be noises in
your office that are not speech.

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:45.900
Door slams, telephone rings, coughs,
paper shuffling.

00:20:45.930 --> 00:20:50.170
We have to make sure that we don't
try to search those in the speech,

00:20:50.170 --> 00:20:53.430
against the speech grammar,
and so we have models for

00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:56.100
lots of sounds like that.

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:59.100
The first thing that happens when
Speech comes into the Recognizer is we

00:20:59.100 --> 00:21:01.320
test it against those models of noise.

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:04.080
And if it matches one of those
better than it matches Speech,

00:21:04.080 --> 00:21:06.580
then we reject it as
being background noise.

00:21:06.660 --> 00:21:10.590
Now we have tuned up the
Speech Recognizer to prefer to

00:21:10.590 --> 00:21:13.280
reject than to make a wrong choice.

00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:17.900
And so it turns out that this rejection
performance is the most sensitive

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:20.900
measure of the performance of a
microphone and of the Recognizer.

