could reliably handle.

01:04:31.300 --> 01:04:32.460
And that was fine.

01:04:32.460 --> 01:04:35.880
It was easy to remember
the set of commands.

01:04:36.060 --> 01:04:38.100
But now that the Recognizer
is so much stronger,

01:04:38.100 --> 01:04:40.560
we're finding we and others
have hundreds of commands.

01:04:40.590 --> 01:04:46.320
The burden is now on the user to remember
the exact wording of those commands.

01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:48.910
And if you get it wrong,
you're out of luck.

01:04:49.040 --> 01:04:50.280
Here's why.

01:04:50.280 --> 01:04:54.240
The way the Recognizer works is that
you load it up with a language model,

01:04:54.460 --> 01:04:57.390
which is a list of what
it's supposed to listen for.

01:04:58.300 --> 01:05:01.270
Then if it hears something
that's in that language model,

01:05:01.280 --> 01:05:01.280
it'll listen for it.

01:05:01.300 --> 01:05:02.770
Then if it hears something
that's in that language model,

01:05:02.770 --> 01:05:04.870
such as, what time is it,
that goes into the search,

01:05:04.870 --> 01:05:07.950
and the search finds which path
through the language model most

01:05:08.300 --> 01:05:09.910
closely matches that utterance.

01:05:10.100 --> 01:05:12.700
Associated with that path
is a speakable action,

01:05:12.730 --> 01:05:15.250
such as, in this case, speaking the time.

01:05:15.260 --> 01:05:19.630
The problem is, what happens if the
person accidentally says,

01:05:19.630 --> 01:05:21.000
what is the time?

01:05:21.020 --> 01:05:24.360
Now you can feed that into the search,
and you know what'll happen?

01:05:24.360 --> 01:05:25.560
Nothing.

01:05:25.560 --> 01:05:28.980
Because there's no path through
the grammar to match that.

01:05:29.030 --> 01:05:31.280
So,
our solution is to use the Recognizer.

